I found this as pro for session: The big difference between sessions and cookies is that the value of the variable will be stored on the server if you're using sessions, and on the client if you're using cookies. I can't think of any good reason to use cookies instead of sessions, except if you want data to persist between sessions, but even then it's perhaps better to store it in a DB, and retrieve it based on a username or id.
but they also write that you should not use sessions if you store much content.  But I can't find out what much is in kB or MB.
<@UJHD6A81H> SessionStorage is fully stored in the client, and you can store a lot of data in it, as long as its a string. But then again, in javascript you can serialize a lot of stuff into strings.
The main disadvantage is, of course, the fact that it only lasts until you close your browser; but LocalStorage will do instead if you need longer-time storage.
Cookies can last as short and as long as you need it, but they're usually optimized for very short strings, like an ID from the server.
Also, while you can look up and replace cookies from javascript, it's far harder to do than using Session/LocalStorage, so maybe take that into account too.

<@UJHD6A81H> It's entirely on the client.
But each domain (or rather, origin) has its separate set of cookies and its separate Session and LocalStorages.

"Origin" is an HTML-specific concept, but it's basically anything in the URL bar before the slash after the domain. <http://bla.com> and <https://bla.com> are different origins, as are <https://bla.com> and <https://bla.com:80>

What is the disadvantage if we use sessions variables directly in the code - I mean I use variables and when I send the page I store the variable into a session variable. Could we use session variables directly?
If it's data that's not gonna be modified from javascript, you save work by not having to push that to the client.

If both the server and the client can modify that data, you'll have to synchronize stuff. You can use the "storage" event to have one single JS function that deals with pushing new changes to the server.
* "storage" event
sorry, I slightly misread the docs, and this isn't an API I use a lot

But again, SessionStorage only lasts for one "session" (until all tabs of your origin are closed). Look into LocalStorage for long-term storage.

As a general rule: if you have to communicate with a server on the web platform, you'll have to tell the API with what server to communicate.
Relative links are no exception, becuase they're relative to the current URL, they don't exist in the void.
